\begin_layout Theorem
The product of two 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-finite measure spaces is itself 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-finite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}=\bigcup C_{i}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i}(s)<\infty$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in C_{i}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 a countable set, for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula \[
C=\{s_{1}\times s_{2}\mid s_{1}\in C_{1}\wedge s_{2}\in C_{2}\}.\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
X_{1}\times X_{2} & = & \left(\bigcup C_{1}\right)\times\left(\bigcup C_{2}\right)\\
 & = & \{(x_{1},x_{2})\mid(\exists s_{1}\in C_{1}.\, x_{1}\in s_{1})\wedge(\exists s_{2}\in C_{2}.\, x_{2}\in s_{2})\}\\
 & = & \{(x_{1},x_{2})\mid\exists s\in C.\,(x_{1},x_{2})\in s\}\\
 & = & \bigcup C.\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset

 are countable, so is 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, if 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in C$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $s=s_{1}\times s_{2}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}\in C_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}\in C_{2}$
\end_inset

, and we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(s)=\mu(s_{1})\mu(s_{2})<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

